<h2>Vigilant Media network</h2>

<h3>Musicwhore.org</h3>

<p>Musicwhore.org started out as a short-lived print zine, then relaunched as a webzine.</p>

<p>In reality, Musicwhore.org is my learning laboratory -- whenever I want to teach myself a new scripting technique, I experiment with Musicwhore.org.</p>

<p>In addition to building an artist directory complete with album and song information, I integrated (and extended) Movable Type as a content manager. Movable Type handles RSS feeds and search, but content delivery is handled by scripts which were adapted from a custom-built CMS I have since obsoleted.</p>

<p>I also built an online store through Amazon.com's XML web services, integrating it with my database of artists, albums and reviews. The store didn't result in a lot of referals, so instead, I paired Amazon's web services with the Musicbrainz web service to deliver globalized content.</p>

<p>A custom-built account system allowed users to listen to streamed MP3s of artists featured on the site. I ran a separate web server to host audio content, which was delivered through ShoutCAST and a free version of RealNetwork's Helix server. I have since shut down the audio server.</p>

<p>I wrote the content of the site as well, translating music news items from Japanese into English and providing album reviews of American and international artists as well.</p>

<p>In September 2005, I relaunched the site as a weblog and turned the webzine into an archive. I also launched a film review site, Filmwhore.org, using the same backend as Musicwhore.org. Filmwhore.org also integrates film information from the Amazon web service with site content. TVwhore.org followed soon after, but both sites have become neglected step-children compared to its older sibling.</p>
